AI Response — Validated Understanding
The AI confirmed the big picture was correct and corrected one key misconception: task_manager.py is NOT the entry point. cli.py is.

Technologies Identified
Library	Purpose
argparse	Reads terminal commands and flags
uuid	Generates unique IDs for each task
enum	Defines fixed categories (priority, status)
datetime	Handles due dates and timestamps
json	Saves and loads task data from disk

Each File's Purpose Explained
File	Purpose
cli.py	Front door — user types commands here (ENTRY POINT)
task_manager.py	The brain — all the logic lives here
models.py	Blueprint — defines what a Task looks like and what it can do
storage.py	Memory — saves/loads tasks to a JSON file on disk
task_priority.py	Scoring algorithm — ranks tasks by importance
task_parser.py	Text parser — converts free text into Task objects
task_list_merge.py	Merge — combines two separate task lists into one
tests/	Automated tests — checks the code works correctly

Application Entry Point
The entry point is cli.py — specifically the main() function at the bottom. This is where Python starts when the app is run. The if __name__ == '__main__': block triggers main(), which sets up all the commands.

# In cli.py — the entry point
if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()

Architecture Pattern
The project follows a Layered Architecture — each layer has one job and only communicates with the layer directly below it:

cli.py          (user input layer)
    |
    v
task_manager.py (business logic layer)
    |
    v
storage.py      (data persistence layer)
    |
    v
tasks.json      (data file on disk)

models.py       (shared across all layers)

